text:
First things first, this is not a hotel - its a hostel. That might not be a problem for you, it wasn't for me, but it's good to be honest, no?
The price of this place was so reasonable that it seems foolish to claim it was terrible, what do you expect for paying next to nothing? The rooms come with beds, plugs, drawers and that's about it. No TVs, no towel racks, no frills.
On my list of priorities was Location, Security and Comfort. So how did it do?
1. Location - Hard to beat. Upper West Side is glorious and some of the bars around are some of the best in NYC (Cleopatra's Needle). The subway is a two minute walk and is on the express line, meaning your in Times Square very quickly.
2. Security - Not great. Our door had a lock that was, well, hard to lock. It didn't turn all the way and left a gap in the door. Not disastrous, but not great. Most worrying was the fact that around said lock, there was a crack that clearly indicated it has been kicked in at some point. The lock had simply been screwed back into the wood and perhaps most shockingly there was sticky tape around the cracks. Put simply - it was a concern for most of the trip.
3. Comfort - Fine, just fine. This category is perhaps more subjective, comfort for Paris Hilton is excessive for Joe Bloggs. However, the beds were good and the heating/cooling system, despite being too loud, worked. You get the BARE minimum, but if that's comfort for you, then it really is fine.
Not a terrible place to stay for those wanting to do NYC on a shoe string. Would I go back? No, but only because of the security worries which you shouldn't be forced to deal with. The staff were lovely and helpful, the rooms cleaned daily and the location great.
label: negative

text:
Overall, a solid choice. It is definitely a busy, hip restaurant, and exactly what you'd expect from the Cosmo. Loud music, cute staff, fun artwork, big, diverse menu, but slightly overpriced.

We came for lunch on a Saturday. There was about a 25 min wait, but given that it is a popular place, we expected that. We each ended up getting cocktails (not the milkshakes). My friend loved her Bloody Mary, and I thought that the XXX was fine, nothing to rave over. Drinks ranged from $10-$13. 

We split the lobster mac & cheese (I believe it was $16). It was a pretty small portion, and I found it to be underseasoned. You could see the lobster in there, so that was a good thing. 

I had the Chicken Carbonnera sandwich, while she had the Gold Standard burger. We were both pleased. My chicken was juicy, I loved the bun and the egg on top, as well as the bacon. We both liked the steak fries (you have a choice of shoestring or steak cut) as well. Portions were about average- not tiny, but you won't leave feeling like you're bursting out of your pants, either.

Service was fine, nothing to complain about, but nothing to rave about either.

Prices..well, for what you get, they may be a bit overpriced, but knowing that it is on the Strip, in the Cosmo...
label: negative

text:
My husband and I stayed at the Surfer Beach Hotel for a weekend getaway. I booked the "junior suite" because we enjoy having the space. The description in Expedia for the junior suite said "...the balcony offers beach/ocean view....". The room given to us was Room 419 which was the corner of the "L" shape building. There were no balcony (other than if you open the front door and stand in the hallway. The extra room only had a sofa bed which would be nice for family with kids and had nothing else. The TV was in the bedroom so if you were sitting on the couch, you would not be able to watch TV. There were 2 TV's in the room, (which was odd) one mount to the wall which wasn't working and one standing on the cabinet which worked but none of the two remote worked for the TV. I noticed all the other "regular" rooms had a balcony and they all faced the ocean but we got the corner "suite" with no balcony or ocean view but we paid for it.
The hotel was an older hotel but you can tell it was renovated which I knew when I booked it. It was at a great location and we enjoyed the sunset...standing in the hallway, at the end of the building, near someone's window. Because of how the rooms were situated, people do walk by your window to get to their rooms. We had people walking by and talking loud, late in the night and early in the morning. There was no air condition and we had the windows open for air but had to shut them because of the noise (music, people talking). Even though the king-size bed was comfortable, my husband and I didn't get a good night sleep.
Also the free internet had very poor signal. We were not able to use the wifi at all during our stay. We would not return to the Surfer Beach Hotel.
label: negative

text:
Came here for the first time for Scran Salon as its not really local for me. Although Hemma means home in Swedish, it didn't give me that vibe, despite the floral chairs on the upstair mezzanine area. 

It is all glass and open, hence not feeling cozy and although we were here for a private event, the noise downstairs travels up so it made hearing people speak a bit awkward. 

So why 4 stars? I had sampled the food and it was great. This was provided as part of the event and was very scandi - salmon, trout, potato salad, veggies with dill, breads and more and it was lovely. Being gluten free, some options were off limits but the trout, meats and cheese were lovely. I only picked at a couple of things as I had eaten before I arrived but what I had was very good. 

So Hemma isn't very local for me but I will be visiting again and if I have the munchies, I would be happy to eat here.
label: neutral

text: 曾经用过TERO 600,NOKIA6630,用过的感受与大家分享:1 机型: 600非常酷,大气,拿到任何场合绝对给十足的面子;6630初步看有点不习惯,但看久了也比较好看.2 机子反映速度: 尽管600的CPU才160HZ,6630的220HZ,二者差不多，好象600快点,主要表现在软件运行速度上.3 软件的专用性: PALM的更专业,更细致,DOCEMENT要比QUCIOFICE好用4 软件的易用性: 6630容易操作,PALM的大部分软件都是英文的,而塞班的中文的多5 系统稳定性: 塞班比PALM稳定6 电话功能: 塞班比PALM好用7 软件操作的便利性: TREO有键盘+触屏,软件操作过程中比塞班的纯键盘方便的多8 待机时间:我的6630如果连续上网一般是10个小时,970A的电池,屏幕亮度调到最低,600由于屏幕分辨率太低,显示效果不好，没有测试过.9机子的可玩性:各有优势,PALM的软件比较专业,需要研究,塞班的简单,容易掌握.10 机子的手感: TREO好

text:
袋には六帝古銭。でも中身は五帝銭。ショップのただの間違いならよいのですが。返品可か？
このページの写真の六帝古銭だと思い注文しました。 ただの間違いならよいのですが、届いた商品の袋には六帝古銭 と書かれておりました。でも、中身をみると写真の結び目は赤い紐 さらに古銭の数は５つ。これはあきらかに5帝銭です。 金額は六帝古銭の金額です。いくらなんでもショップの方の封入ミス だと思うのですが、五帝銭はこの金額の半額で購入できます。 また、自分は用途が違うので、六帝古銭でないと困ります。 こういう品物は類似品が多いので、最初のメインページで 表示されている商品は、画面右横の欄から同じショップの 商品が確実に購入できる、さらに類似品やほかのショップの商品は 類似品としてクリックすると購入する画面にしてもらわないと 困ります。大陸の品物はこういう行き違いがあったりするので（これらの 類の品物は2回目。）商品個別にそれぞれの写真の正確な表示があれば、 どれを選べるかわかりやすいので、Amazonさんのほうで そういうページ構成にしてもらえると目的の商品が確実に買えて 助かります。
label: negative

text:
My family and I just stayed there a couple of weeks ago due to its proximity to our house which was being worked on. We stayed 4 nights, and it was not too bad. Although we pretty much just slept there, we found the room to be spacious, fairly clean, albeit dark and stuffy. The bathroom was clean but very very small - no counter space! And the shower was just plain weird (no tub) but clean.
The bedspreads (we had 2 beds) did not look that clean, so I examined the blankets and sheets closely. Found a few gray hair in the blankets! Yup. Sure did. I quickly asked for clean flat sheets to cover our blankets. Oh, and I pulled off the bedspreads entirely. The next day and went home and took our beddings with us. I know this is not an option for most people, but because I could, therefore I did.
The breakfast was buffet style and consisted of bread and bagels which you can toast yourself, pasties, hard boiled eggs, juice, coffee & tea. Although it wasn't the greatest, it was good to have. In the evening they serve fresh baked Otis Spunkmeyer cookies, and we enjoyed them, of course.
The parking was not too bad, but the spaces are small and narrow. The hotel was not full that week so we always found a space, but it would be hard if it were full.
The pool was very small and didn't look that clean so we never used it.
The evening clerk was extremely nice and responsive. Had a problem with the remote and the repairman came very quickly. The day staff was so so.
Housekeeping was okay. Don't know if they change the blankets and bedspreads with each guest, and don't know if the hair simply got stuck to the blankets even after washing (which happen sometimes). Since I brought our own beddings, I didn't want anyone to mess with our beds so I asked them to only remove the trash and replace the towels, and they were happy to oblige.
Would I stay there again? Probably if we had work done on the house again, but I'll remember to bring my own comforter.
label: negative

text: Stayed two nights with wife for leisure. Pros are 1) location - just blocks from the Circle with all the shopping, restaurants and clubs (consider Slippery Noodle for blues). 2) large rooms - not true two room suites with door between but quite large with two TVs. 3) relatively new and nice. 4) kitchenette if you need that. Cons 1) management inept - we were out of our room from 10A to 4P, returned for a nap before dinner only to find still no maid service. Apparently housekeeping starts on the first floor and works their way up (we were on 5). Hotel not near full (? 1/3 at most) so seems they could have gotten to stay overs sooner - maybe this is the most efficient/economical way to do it but unacceptable in our eyes, you may not agree, but major issue for us. 2) elevator very slow and no front stairwell. 3) Wood area in kitchenette sticky both days - ? mop. 4) Returned to room after maid left and dishwasher running - one water glass we had used in it total - so much for economical. 5) breakfast is included in room charge but other than ubiquitous self made waffles the hot portion was pretty rough sledding - plan on continental. 5) may want to rename it the Homeless Suites. Sadly on way to Circle there were 4-5 beggars all the time. Hadn't noted this in Indy before - ? maybe the time of year. Room noise others have noted not a problem on 5th floor but with the poor maid service and really slow elevator (can't imagine if it had been close to full) would avoid top floor. Otherwise hotel reasonable choice for downtown.
label: negative

text: It has definite pros: the location is great, the lobby is beautiful, the staff was pleasant and professional. However, I have NEVER stayed in such a stripped-down room ANYWHERE. The bathroom is tiny, with a pedestal sink and no counter. Shampoo, conditioner and soap ONLY. No lotion. No shower cap. No coffee. No wet bar. No free internet. Paper-thin walls through which we could easily overhear our neighbors' conversations. The whole place is torn up right now - one entrance open, no fitness center to speak of, workers, tarps, and paint fumes galore. If you're thinking Hilton = four star luxury like I was, you are so wrong. DO NOT pay anything close to rack rate. If I hadn't gotten such a deal on the rate, I would have been furious.
label: negative

text: Looking for a place to eat to eat we stumbled across Tokyo Teppan for lunch. We ate with the lunchtime crowd, but it wasn't packed, we could easily get a table. We had the Ten Don and Tempura Bento sets, which came with a MYO salad, miso soup and dessert (fruit in a yuzu syrup). The meal was good, not the best Japanese I've had. For our party of two, the meal came up to RM75, including two green teas. The bento boxes/ set sizes were generous. Dimmed lighting, modern decor makes for a good meal. RM29 for a bento box I find is very reasonable, though for most restaurants in Malaysia, tack on a 6% sales tax and 10% service charge to the bill.
label: positive

text:
I'm gonna just put it out there... pizza is awesome anytime. It's even more amazing when you're drunk. THERE, I said it. So when we left Tao Beach, tipsy and needing some nosh, Otto Enoteca was there to save us from making another Dal Toro mistake. 
Service was outstanding for sure. The hostess was sweet and didn't even seem to care that we looked like little drowned rats (and we were too hungry to care). The server and his assistant were very personable and even gave hugs when requested (albeit very tentatively... probably not something they are asked for on the reg). Waters were always filled and our request for extra napkins was fulfilled quickly. 
The pizza... ohhhhhh that pizza. The four of us shared a Margherita 'D.O.C.' and the Pesto, which was perfect between all of us. I love pesto anything, so I was in pesto heaven (if you can't guess which pizza I'm talking about, we can't be friends... in fact, stop reading right meow). The Margherita was bomby as well, but come on.... PESTO. Best of all, it didn't break the bank whatsoever. Obviously, the bill would have been larger had we been imbibing, but for food and good times people watching (on the "patio"), I would definitely return... and I plan to. 


PESTO!

text:
We stayed at the Omni Hotel at end of June as we had one night in LA before we flew out the next day and didn't want to be stuck around the airport. We read the reviews and got a great rate at the hotel.
This hotel is just a really nice, quite classy hotel. Its downtown so perfect if you have business in that district but as one of the other reviews mentioned, there is a nice mall next door. The day we were there a small music festival was going on at the mall which made it all the better.
Fabulous rooms, extremely comfortable beds and friendly service. If you haven't got the impression from all the other reviews, the bed in our room may be the best I have slept in at a hotel.
Can't really say enough things about the hotel - I know that one of the reviews mentioned the mini bar could be better (??) but I don't pick hotels by mini-bar - there was a lovely bar within the hotel that should most people busy....
Keep up the good work Omni!
label: positive

text:
this place was perfect for my family. we rented 4 one bedroom suites side by side.
each suite opens to a small hallway and main door. the doors to each suite easily stay open - and feels safe because they're behind the main, locked door.

there were four men. i'm 50+ and my older brother met me and my 25 year old son and his buddy there. each of us having our own bathroom and bedroom was awesome. we regularly hung out in the living room of each other's space like it was a college dorm! this setup also worked out perfectly when my wife came to join us after we had been there 4 days with just all the guys - we closed our suite door and maintained our privacy.

the full sized refrigerators and ranges, as well as full kitchens were key to it being the perfect place for us. even if we had additional people that needed to sleep on the couch, there's plenty of wardrobe (hanging) and deep dresser like storage.

the dining room table was awesome as well, since we needed someplace to sit after cooking - ha

the wifi would be my only complaint. it's expensive and only 2 devices can be on at one time. really lame. almost inconceivable. plus, you have to constantly log in. pain in the butt and full of gaul IMHO. the reasons to use wifi are plenty on a vacation, including uploading our photos for backup purposes and to share with fam and friends. 

if the grandview's wifi policy was normal, it would enhance the experience and people might write better reviews about the wifi nazi's...

we stayed in the daisy and got hip real quick to parking in the covered garage at the end. the kiddie pool was right across from us. the "main" pools are in building 2 and is also where the very handy deli is located. the pools are different though! 

the temperature of the upper pool is what you'd expect when the temps are 104-110 degrees. mildly refreshing. the lower pool with the waterfall will knock your socks off!!! it might be 70 degrees or even less! it's the maximum refresher! we were so chilly after sitting in the cooler water for a while, that we actually got a chill -- and it was 107 degrees outside!!!! 

we never visited any other pools, so i don't have any intel on their conditions. oh yea, the deli is a rare gem; they have lots of things you might need in a pinch, but you can also call down in advance. they might have said they deliver, but i can't recall.

the other great option is the south point casino right next door. first, it is totally within walking distance. second, there's a short cut just out the gate past the check in office. cross the street and walk up the steps to the side door!!! it may say emergency exit on it, but the employees at the grandview said they go in and out that way all the time.

they have a burger and shake place that's great; one of the restaurants serves breakfast which is inexpensive and tasty too. the roulette tables have $1.00 minimums, not the $5 mins like in the heart of the strip. i think someone else mentioned the convenience of such a large casino in the close proximity of the grandview. this could keep you down at the south end without ever hitting the mix of the strip or fremont street. 

but to us, it was an ace in the pocket; we used it in a pinch to buy lunch before heading out to drop my brother and son's friend at the airport. cheap and easy.

i drove up from san diego so we could have easy transportation while there. it was a genius move on my part. turns out almost every casino/hotel on the strip has free "self" parking! it was a snap to get in and out - mind you it's august and not the prime season and no huge events going on. but i got us all around the city, strip, to and from the airport (the I-15 is 2 minutes away), and down to the fremont street experience, and even to sapphire, the gentleman's club by driving - and using my iphone and the new google maps!

i would not say i'm a technology connoisseur, but an avid fan of making my life easier. the new google maps lets you "search" just like you would do when using google's main search engine - but it immediately maps from where you are to that place. and it does it with minimal screens and steps. i also used a blutooth handsfree device from costco that sits on my sun visor. since i didn't have an actual navigator (aka my wife), i would just search for where we were going, it pulls it up and then i'd hit "start route" and off we'd go. even if we changed our minds mid trek, i could do almost everything i needed to pretty quickly - say, illegally at a stop light, or puling over - and have the new route being spoken to the entire car in seconds.

since LV is so hot, we used the a/c all the time. this also allowed me to stream my pandora or slacker right to the blutooth and we could all jam. the upside to this is that it would pause the music when google maps needed to speak a new instruction - no turning down the music or missing the information! it was sweet.
label: neutral

text: 作者将注意力集中在了酒店集团企业理念的类比和个案举例,对于集团之间的差异和对比缺乏深入的思考,通篇都是对著名酒店企业理念举例的排列组合,而且数据资料滞后,谈不上研究。 读这本书的初衷在于通过对这些集团企业理念的比较后,得出他们之间的差异,通过这些不同从而能对这些集团的客源划分、经营优势得出一个可供参考的结论,目前看来,至少没有达到我的期望。 书中学术气息很强,不适合实战型的经理人阅读,对于初涉酒店的管理人员来说则有很高的参考价值,因为通过阅读本书可以开拓眼界,寻找这些著名酒店管理集团之间的契合点来提升自身能力。 总监及以上职位的管理人员,去看一本《康奈德品牌手册》也比这个来得实在。
label: negative

text: L'amateur de (bons) giallos restera sur sa faim et si Nue pour l'assassin comporte bien son lot de nudité et de meurtres il est regrettable que le réalisateur préféra s'attarder sur le "Nue" du titre que sur le mot "assassin" d'ailleurs dans la première demi-heure on apprécie énormément la présence de la sexy Femi Benussid'ailleurs avec sa disparition disparaîtra le peu d'intérêt que l'on porte pour ce giallo. On regrette que les scènes de meurtre sont dans l'ensemble assez faibles surtout que l'ouverture était pas mal suivi du générique accompagné d'une belle musique mais le reste fera défaut, l'enquête n'est pas intéressante à suivre, les personnages manquent de profondeur mais c'est l'absence de suspense, de rythme et d'un climat inquiétant qui manque totalement à Nue pour l'assassin pour en faire un giallo réussi. Donc ce thriller transalpin ne fait pas du tout partie des incontournables du genre.

text: Заезжали 26.02.2023 воскресенье, после 4х выходных, большой поток посетителей. Заказали 2 плова(цена порции 265 рублей за 200 грамм), макароны с нагетсами, 2 капучино и компот. Ребенок ел нагетсы и макароны ничего против не имел, так как наггетсы Мираторг, компот тоже норм. Но плов это что то с чем то, мало того что все в залито подсолнечным масло так и соли как в солёной рыбе, естественно есть не возможно. Попросили повара попробовать свой плов, на что сразу сказал что выбирайте любое другое блюдо. Чтобы хоть что то поесть взяли взамен гречку и куриные котлеты под сырной майонезной коркой(хотя сказали что там филе) опять прогадали. Гречка обычная, но котлеты снова были соленые как копчёная рыба, непонятно под какой солью готовил повар все это. Отдельно кофе, спросили это зерновой кофе? На что ответили, что да, в итоге вкус Нескафе растворимого с сухим молоком. Цена качество не соответствует ожиданиям. В соседним кафе через дорогу еда намного вкуснее и дешевле.
label: negative

text:
I usually come here to pickup a few baguettes that are fresh and right out of the oven. Despite this, I will have to agree on some of the recent negative ratings. 

They are really stingy on the ingredients. For example, a 4-dollar Thai ice tea I ordered contained over 50% ice, and when I asked them to remove some ice and replace it with more tea, they refused and said something to the effect that refills were not allowed even though I had not yet consumed any. 

On a side note, there is a sign at the register that reads, "in order to keep prices low we only accept cash." In my opinion, their prices are fair, but by no means low.

In the future, I certainly won't go out of my way to patronize this establishment. I'll be doing them a favor since I don't want to break their profit margin by asking for less ice in the drinks!
label: negative

text: Добрый день. Длительное время пользуюсь продуктами Банка и всегда был очень доволен, но тут проризошел интересный случай... У меня 2 карты кредитная Урбан Мастер Карт и дебеторая виртуальная Карта плюсов Мастер кард с бесплатным обслуживанием. Позвонил в колл-центр, чтобы уточнить, могу ли я выпустить дополнительные карты платежной системы МИР к кредитной и деботовым картам платежной системы Мастер Кард. Получил утвердительный ответ, да приезжайте в отделение и пишите заявление на выпуск дополнительных карт. Приехал в отделение АШАН-Сокольники 17.12.2022. Сотрудники были немного не в курсе ситуации и не могли определиться, как им оформить карты МИР, как перевыпуск мастер карта или как дополнительные. В итоге оформили, как дополнительные, которые должны доставить в отделение в течение двух недель. Дело сделано, довольный покинул отделение банка. Прошло 10 минут времени, мне звонит сотрудница отделения и сообщает, что дополнительную карту к дебетовой карте плюсов оформить нельзя. Надо её закрывать и открывать МИР, только уже на платной основе. На возражение, что сотрудники КЦ утверждают, что дополнительную карту оформить можно, получил ответ, что сотрудники КЦ мне предоставляют некорректную информацию. Сразу же позвонил в КЦ, где мне опять сказали, что оформление доп карты МИР возможно, так как по моей карте плюсов новая программа лояльности. Сотрудница приняла от меня претензию. Как всегда, из-за некомпетентности сотрудников (пока неизвестоно КЦ или отделения), страдают клиенты, которые тратят личное время и деньги на посещение отделений. На основании вышесказанного, прошу дать ответ, кто всё-таки был прав? Сотрудники колл-центра или сотрудники отделения банка? Также жду от Вас ответ на мою претензию, зафиксированную 17.12.2022.
label: negative

text: The title of this book is a phrase used by the British and Americans during World Wars 1 and 2 to indicate continental Europe, where the fighting was taking place. This book was written during World War 1. The Western Front in the subtitle is the line where the westward-moving German army was being met by the armies of the countries they were invading. Arnold Bennett was a novelist who was Director of Propaganda for France at the Ministry of Information during the war. That's the background, on to the book...Bennett tells of the time he spent moving from town to town in France and Belgium along the Front. He is always escorted by a military officer, and they often walk through trenches and have to take cover if an artillery shell explodes nearby. He frequently goes into detail about towns and buildings that have been damaged or destroyed by the Germans. It's not a very personal book- he seldom writes about people he meets or relates conversations. Occasionally he muses on the absurdity of what the Germans are doing, and what it is costing in terms of people's lives and livelihoods. His cynicism shines through at those moments. The book will be best enjoyed by war buffs, but it's short, and an excellent description of a war zone, so I recommend it to people who don't normally read war books as well.
label: positive

text:
I stayed here on a combination business/pleasure trip. I had never stayed at a W before although have stayed at many Starwood properties before. This hotel is not for everyone but it is for alot of people, myself included. It is in the financial district so there is not alot going on in the general area for tourists, but if you are a tourist and are aware of that, then you will have no problem.
You will need to take the elevator up to get to the check in area and then another set of elevators to get to the rooms. The hotel is entirely non smoking and has great views from some of the rooms, especially of the Ground Zero and memorial area. The fitness center was well appointed and I had it to myself most of the time.
The rooms are bright and well appointed with ammenities for both business and pleasure. For example. there was candy from Dylan's but also highlighters in the desk should I need them. I was upgraded to a Corner Cool room which means I had wrap around windows. The room is really not different from other rooms.
This hotel is definately not traditional so therefore, not for everyone however if you like Ws and something a bit different and are aware you are in the Financial District, then you will like this hotel. I would definately stay there again.
label: positive

text: What a big disappointment! We were expecting great Cantonese cuisine, but what did we get? First, steamed scallop ON a shell, literally! because the scallop was already detached and just placed onto the shell with a big dollop of chopped garlic on top and hardened glass noodle underneath. Garlic tasted raw and the scallop rubbery! RM23 per rubbery scallop mind you.Second dish is grilled spare ribs "supposedly" marinated in red wine. No taste of wine, just plain sweet and nothing else. The little meat there was, was stuck stubbornly to the bone.. it was not a melt in the mouth moment! Each portion is just one bite size and one of my friend's "bite" was just bone! Each bite size is RM10.Ok, admittedly the stir fried vege (RM48) and eggplant in hotpot (RM28) were acceptable but nothing to shout about.Next, the steamed free ranged chicken c/w steamed rice. hmm.. why is it not steaming hot? and where is the aroma of steamed chicken?? The meat was soft and flaky (like ordinary chicken), tasted flat and like its been frozen for ages. The condiments of ginger and chilli blend did not help at all. Sorry to say, the chicken rice sold in my neighborhood tasted way better than this. Half free ranged chicken cost RM108.Our above concerns were conveyed to the head waitress. She put on a blank face while listening and mumbled she will inform the chef of our comments and walked away.I used to love eating at Ming, not anymore!
label: negative

text:
I was puzzled by the positive reviews on Trip advisor for this hotel. Then after reading them again after I stayed here for 5 nights it occured to me that most travelers must be in a very relaxed state of mind when they stay here. When I travel on business I put in 10-12 hrs days regularly. As such quality service and efficiency matter to me. When vacationing I typically have a higher tolerance for poor service, less quality food, and the like. So I will not stay again at this hotel. I'll list my likes and dislikes .
Likes: Architecture is historic. Rooms comfortable and quiet, well equiped. The transportation shuttle service. Excellent offering and a life saver given the seedy character and deserted streets in Downtown (at least when it is after 6 pm.) Rooms are large and the bathroom is fabulous and even larger. Love the tub and shower. Quality ammentities. TV is large and has High definition channels. Maintenance was responsive and professional
Dislikes: Food at restaurant : Unhealthy, over priced, Incredible slow service, servers and bar personnel are more interested in talking with each other than servicing the guests Took 25 min for soup and salad at 9:30 pm. Soup was luke warm --I guess the microwave was not working since it would not pass a kitchen inspection if served this temp. Likely kept in the fridge and microwaved to heat up. If on a diet this is not the place to eat...except for salads Ordered a cucumber and tomatoe salad. Not exagerating 20 min to recieve and Approx 1/4 of a tomato, 1/8 of a cucumber, 3 bits of feta cheese , 1 slice of onion, a couple bits of shredded mint and maybe 20 pepitas . and I added 2 shrimp This very very small salad cost 13 $. 1/2 cup of soup was $7. I'm a lite eater and I left very hungry. Front Desk personnel are inconsistent. Ranged from excellent to disinterested.
label: negative

text: This is the book that ruined me for all "average" romance novel about lithe super fabulous women who looked like a million bucks and get the man of their dreams, yeah, like that's what the ideal woman looks like.After years of frustrating romance reading we have a burgeoning genre of BBW/Curvy romance authors that are striving to give the readers what we crave, a shred of realism amongst the fantasy... that not all women are size 0-10, and that a man can be just attracted to a "curvy" woman as he is to a reed thin super model.Fall From Troy is about a woman Angie who goes on a Cruise with her friend Corrie looking for romance, but what she comes to find out is she feels very out of place amongst the sexually liberated men and women on board the ship having the time of their lives in full view, she begins to compare her curvy body to the taut and tight bodies around her and feels insecure about how she looks.That is until she's spotted by Troy Hunter, he sees the curvy brunette hiding behind a potted plant and he can't take his eyes off her, when she makes her leave, he finds himself following her and let's just say that's where the heat really gets turned up.We have the classic formula of our couple not believing that this is anymore than a weekend tryst, Troy believes his future is with a blond, willowly beauty that will be the mother of his children but as time goes by feelings begin to emerge and Troy can't get Angie off his mind.While there were a few moments in this book that I could have done with out... I enjoyed this book so much that I've been on the hunt for every BBW romance ever since and I'm still going strong.Enjoyable book... very hot and heavy so if your not into explicit love scenes, then this book isn't for you.
label: positive

text: Over the GW is a near failure of a debut feature, and not because it's not without trying...Actually, it is. It's a shamble all the more because it's writer/director/technical everyman Nick Gaglia went through the same rehab cult that he depicts in the film. Sometimes a first time filmmaker, full of the vigor that comes with getting a thumbs up or two from fellow film students, goes headlong into style that is way too disjointed, unsure, and dramatically frustrating that the personal side of the story, the extremely personal side, gets smudged in the purpose of telling a good story. Gaglia, who was 13 when put into a horrid program that basically tortured and brainwashed their "patients" with crazy group scare tactics, psychological mind-f*** sessions that could go on for days, and attitudes from the rehab leaders that would make most Nazis cringe, escaped finally when he was 15. I'm glad he got out, though it might help if he now goes into a real rehab for his film-making skills, if only for a couple of days, to learn things like, say, structure, proper lighting, fluid camera movement, subtlety with actors, and other basics that are perpetually lost here.It's all the more frustrating because Gaglia is dealing with a subject that should be shown more to the public (there was recently a Newsweek article referring to a similar AA cult-rehab). Many times one wonders if certain personal character studies might work better as documentaries as opposed to narrative dramas. This is an ever-nagging sensation throughout Over the GW, where it almost feels like Gaglia wants to tell the truth but doesn't know how to communicate it properly through his characters. The character that one would think is closest to him, Bronx teen Tony Serra (Gallagher), who is taken by his mother to a rehab in New Jersey, would be closest to Gaglia, is actually much more of a one-dimensional being, where there is very little back-story (we see a brief freak-out, in black and white, in his old home) and little connection to his mother (Moriarty), who has more potential that is never tapped aside from a cold stone who passes her kids off to another. But there is a story to go with his two-year crisis, I guess.Right off the bat things get rough (a nude cavity search in the first five minutes), and soon it's clear that instead of medical care it's more like a cross between anger management and some bizarre religious sect, where the head doctor Hiller (Insinnia) is a total over-controlling loon. But soon Tony's sister Sofia (Donohue) gets thrown in to the program, and as opposed to Tony's repeated moments of outrage and supposed non-compliance, she goes head-on through the whacked-out three step program and once released becoming a runaway. At times there are bits in this fractured nightmare, where there's one woman, a 22 year old mother who has been in the program a year and a half finds she's become a prisoner not allowed to leave, and when the father of the main siblings comes and pays an enraged visit to Hiller when Sofia finally returns to them, that do contain some raw power, very brief glimpses of Gaglia being able to at least garner some leverage in pure melodrama.But these are moments few and far between. It's not just the unsuccessful characters, who are mostly reduced to stereotypes that veer into being like hysterical D.A.R.E. rip-offs (maybe some of them, like an angry black youth, the passive-aggressive counselors, or even Serra's older sister who is ratted out by the siblings as having taken a hit off a joint and almost thrown into the program, would resonate more if there was more time given to develop any of them). It's that Gaglia is so unfocused in his multiple roles on his tiny $30,000 budget that not one side of whatever potential talent he has can come through. He over-uses tints, mostly with a shade that looks urine-coated), he jiggles his hand-held DVX camera as if it's supposed to be intense ala City of God, occasionally a character will just shoot into frame randomly, his choices of music are like the worst selections possible from pseudo-indie soft-rockers, and there's even inane fake interview scenes with Nicholas Serra (inspiration ?) and Krakowsky that feel about as false as possible.Could Gaglia just not get any interviews with the real victims he was with and resort to would-be artistically cathartic plan B? Bottom line, no matter how much from-the-heart true life stories may appeal to you, don't bother seeing it in the theater, or even on rental, unless you love a final scene with two kids staring off into the digital-hued Hudson river sunset with the final words reading: Dedicated to the Kids. Oy.
label: negative

text: Мною была совершена покупка заемными средствами по карте Халва. Покупка оказалась неудачной, поэтому я оформила возврат. Но возврат денежных средств от продавца обычно занимает около 2 недель. За это время банком была списана комиссия за использование заемных средств у продавца, который НЕ является партнером Совкомбанка. Практика обычная и это является одним из условий при использовании заемных средств. Но! Я же оформила возврат и соответственно эти заемные средства мне не понадобились. Я позвонила в колл-центр Совкомбанка, объяснила ситуацию и была приятно удивлена тем, как быстро был решен мой вопрос. Хотя возврат заемных денежных средств еще не прошел, сотрудница колл-центра вошла в мое положение и отменила комиссию банка, деньги вернулись мне на карту буквально через пару минут. text:
My husband and I recently spent four nights at this hotel. We found it agreeably decorated and clean, convenient to public transportation and restaurants, and located in a neighborhood we like.
As other reviewers have noted, the rooms are barely large enough for the bed; there is insufficient space to open a medium-sized suitcase, nowhere to sit but on the bed, a small bedside table on one but not both sides of the bed, minimal closet space, a lack of shelves in the bathroom for toiletries. Our room had one small window looking out on a brick wall almost close enough to touch, so almost no daylight penetrated; another reading light over the bed would have been welcome (and the possibility of turning the lights on and off from both sides of the bed would have been useful too). Notwithstanding the absence of a street view, traffic from nearby 8th Avenue was clearly audible.
Staff at the desk was very amiable. However, despite time-consuming discussions with a technical assistance number, we had an Internet connection for only about half our stay. The room was provided with an electric coffee/tea maker, but during our stay the coffee and tea supply was never replenished.
All in all, it's a pretty good hotel. But it is woefully overpriced, and I say this from the viewpoint of a couple one of whom spends nights in New York several times a month; we are familiar with New York prices. Good things may come in small packages, but the price isn't right for this small package. Because of the poor price-quality ratio, I would be unlikely to return.
label: neutral

text:
Our first visit to Cherry on Top, and it was good. It did not dethrone Yogurtland as my #1 favorite, but I liked it a smidgen better than Menchies.

I had Oatmeal Cookie, Caramel, Chocolate, and Cappuccino and, as usual, skipped the toppings. I tasted all of them first, so I knew I'd like them.

This stuff is thicker than all the other brands. That doesn't make it taste better or worse, it just made me take, pay for, and ultimately consume more than I wanted. And that's not good, especially the eating part. There is no way to get "just a dab," not even in the little tasting cups, which blob up and over just as soon as the froyo hits the cup. I don't think it's an accident. One of our group picked up the packet that has all the nutritional information, and we were surprised at how high the calorie and sugar count is. I also wasn't happy to learn that high fructose corn syrup figures prominently in the ingredients for all the flavors. But I won't take away stars until I get to compare the competitors' info.

We came here after yet another blah dinner at Outside Inn, which has U-Swirl in the same shopping center, but we wanted to give the newest contender a shot. They have great hours - open till 11 weekdays and until midnight Friday and Saturday, so we'll be back.

text: I know that some films (I mean: European films), that are very bad films, are being regarded as great cinema by certain "critics", only because they're non-American. I saw the 8.1 IMDB score for this film and noticed the fact that this was being selected for certain big festivals. Don't let this fool you! Unless you're one of those people that likes mind-numbing films like this, and call it great art afterwards, skip it! The film contains one hilarious scene after another (a similar, Italian, film popped into my mind, the terrible PREFERISCO IL RUMORE DEL MARE (I prefer the sound of the sea)). The problem with these films is that they're not only boring, like some other strangely praised films, but that they almost play like camp. I mean, let's face it, the acting is horrible (I mean: soap opera-level), the story has not one surprise (this has been done endless times before, connecting several storylines: SHORT CUTS, MAGNOLIA, PLAYING BY HEART, only much better), not one realistic character in it (some true freak-seeing along the way, notice the hilarious zombie-like daughter), and so on and so on.As if that's not enough, the film is 135 min. (count it!) long, and at the end the director opens his can of sentimentality. After a film with such hilariously bad dialogue and scenes that made the public at the preview screening laugh at so much incompetence, well... This is an insult to cinema, and only receives high ratings because it happens to be in "another" language, in this case Spanish. Strange world we live in...3/10
label: negative

text:
I stayed here over President’s Day weekend. I chose it for the price and for its historic status. I’m also into ghosts and it’s supposed to be haunted. I didn’t see any ghosts, but as others have said the hallways do feel kind of creepy, especially at night. They are so long and quiet. Feels like “The Shining” in those hallways. I even saw a door with a penny-size hole cut thru it, but I wasn’t going to look thru it. My lights flickered sometimes. For the bedside light I found out the light bulb was loose. But did a ghost unscrew them all to make them flicker? DA DA DA! I couldn’t check the light bulbs in the ceiling flickering. Not sure how a person would get to that one to unscrew it without a ladder. I have a “ghost radar” app on my phone and right before nightfall I asked “Are there any ghosts here?” and a voice came out of the phone saying “Soon”.
My room was on the 6th floor. The first room they sent me to had not been made. The bed was a mess and there were towels all over the floor. When I went back down to tell the person at the front desk who assigned me that room, she said her computer showed the room HAD been made. Maybe some of your famous ghosts messed it up? I was apologized to and given another room on the 6th floor, one that had been made. It had a view of a fence and beyond that the pool.
My room had a full size 4-poster bed. Be careful getting up in the middle of the night, my head ran into one of the 4 posters. As others have mentioned, the rooms are small, but I was alone so it wasn’t a big deal. I wouldn’t recommend a regular room if there are more than two people in your group. The bathroom was small too. The door swings in and blocks/hides the toilet, so to use the toilet you have to go in, squeeze yourself against the sink, and swing the door closed. Careful you don’t hit yourself with it. The faucets are the old fashioned kind in keeping with the historical nature of the hotel, but they do have sharp little screw-like things sticking out from under the handles, which hurt my hands quite a few times. The sink drained slow. The shower was good and adjustable for different kinds of sprays. There was a power strip in the room, which was good since electrical outlets were hard to fine. There was an ironing board and iron in the closet. No fridge, just an ice bucket. I can’t believe it’s the 21st century and we still have to use ice buckets. All hotel rooms should have mini-refrigerators in them in this day and age. It’s not 1950 anymore.
Like others I will also complain about the old kind of TV’s they have. Not only are they the old tube kind, but they are the kind with curved screens, so they are even worse quality than the flat-screen tube TVs. They really need to upgrade to LCD or plasma TV’s. The bed itself sort of sank in the middle and it was quite noisy when you moved in it. The towels were hard and scratchy. Two of the pillows were flat as a pancake and the other two looked fat but offered no support. When you put your head on them the pillows caved in around your head, like it was a trash bag filled with air. An old Gatorade bottle was on top the armoire. Some stains were noticed in the room and in the hallways. I realize this is an old hotel and some things can be forgiven, but cleanliness and guest comfort has nothing to do with the hotel’s age.
I liked the old historic features like the glass door knobs in the room, dark wood doors, and the wood rectangles above each room door. You can tell those were once the space for the glass tilting windows for airflow, like you see in old movies. Lots of old pictures in the lobby showing famous people who have stayed there and had events held there.
I had breakfast in the hotel restaurant. A little pricey at $12.95 (not including tip) if you want the breakfast buffet. The same breakfast food other chains offer for free. The lobby of the hotel is quite opulent and will make you feel like you are living a few tax brackets above your actual one. People were taking pictures of each other in the lobby to show to their friends. Right next to the front desk you can buy snacks, water, drinks, etc. The prices were good. $1 for a bottle of water, not $3.49 like they charge in the airport. They really shouldn’t call it the “St. Anthony Riverwalk”, since it’s not right on the Riverwalk. It’s close enough to walk to the Riverwalk, Alamo, and other attractions though. The hotel has three entrances. There’s a Walgreen’s close by where you can buy cheap souvenirs and also food items.
All the staff were friendly and helpful, offering me maps and providing other assistance such as calling taxis for me. My overall assessment of the hotel is that it just needs some sprucing up to return to the grandeur of what it once and could be again. If the rest of the hotel looked like the incredible lobby, things would be great. Right now the highest rating I can give it is three “dots”,
label: negative

text:
A hidden gem! 

We never knew this place existed and stumbled into it after lunch at Chino Bandito (next door). They have all sorts of flavors of popcorn and are more than willing to let you sample them. Even some seasonal flavors. We were really excited about the Cake Batter flavor but we sampled it in the store and were a little disappointed in the lack of cake batter flavoring, too much spoiling by Cold Stone's ice cream flavor I guess. 

We took advantage of the bakers dozen deal on the small snack size bags so we could try lots of flavors, it was 13 bags for $11 (normally $1 each). They were even willing to make us a bag of a flavor if we didn't see it in the small size. 

They have many more flavors than what's on their website, some of the ones we got were Churro, Bacon & Cheese, Cookies & Crème, Coconut, PB & Chocolate, Cherry Chocolate and Candy Bar. 

The store had lots of cute tins/gift ideas so next time you are trying to come up with a gift idea for someone, this might just be a great alternative option to the classic gift card.

text:
Rustler's Rooste is a venerable Phoenix tradition.

Many people have come here and had a great time.

I last came here for an event with former students from my college, so my experience is probably atypical.

Our event was part update on whats happening on campus, part memorial, and quite traditional. We do it every year. This was perhaps, the wrong venue for us. We did not have the solemn atmosphere that the memorial part of the event demands, and the other groups around us were having so much fun that I could barely hear the speaker.

No wait staff were required for our group, so I can't tell what service might be like as a regular diner. Our meal was a buffet style bbq chicken dinner, which I probably would avoid if I could. It was a bit overdone, to the point where it may have been better to skip the chick half and make do with the beans (bland), corn (waterlogged cobbettes), rolls (good for crumbs, but not much else), and the afterthought salad.

If I didn't know that much of my fee was going to scholarships, I'd think that I got ripped off.
label: negative

前作は「ゾンビ」と言う奇特な状況とミステリアスで魅力的なホームズに引っ張られてワクワクして読みましたが、今作はクローズドサークルにも魅力がなく、ホームズとも随分親しくなりその分ミステリアスな魅力は失われているように感じます。 他のキャラクターにも魅力的な人物はおらず、そのためミステリーの根幹である殺人の部分で読者を引っ張らねばならないのですが、そこも「予言」という状況を上手く使いこなすことができていない印象です。 前作は「ゾンビ」、今作は「予言」と筆者のやりたい作風はわかるのですが、どうも惰性とまでは言いませんが作風を乗り越えて面白いものを作る魅力を手に入れなければ、読んでいて楽しい小説にはならないのではないかと思いました。

text: Добрый день! 9 января 2023 года я оформил заявку на кредитную карту 180 дней без процентов от Газпромбанка. Для меня это был первый продукт данного банка . 19.01.23 приехал курьер, который привез карту и произвел оформление. Мне был передан конверт с картой и названо название мобильного приложение, через которое я сам должен ее активировать и установить пинкод. При попытке войти в приложение по номеру карты и коду, появлялась ошибка - обратитесь в банк или на горячую линию. Стоит отметить, что горячая линия - это минимум 15 минут ожидания и абсолютно неквалифицированный персонал, который не знает, по какой акции я оформил карту, когда мне начислят обещанный кэшбэк, как карту активировать и тд. На мой вопрос почему я не могу попасть в онлайн-банк был дан ответ, что нужно подождать пока карта прогрузится в системе , и повторить попытку входа. Обычно на вторые сутки после оформления картой можно пользоваться и в ЛК войдете без проблем - сказала мне оператор. Ок, ждем сутки и пытаемся войти 13.01.23 - то же отсутствие результата. Причем оператор по кодовому слову, которое я установил при оформлении карты отказывается меня обслуживать, ссылаясь что оно не верное - хотя я во всех банках уже на протяжении 10 лет использую одно и то же слово. Оператор настаивает, что мне в 2023 году, когда у остальных банков все летает по воздуху и везде диджитал, мне нужно отложить все свои дела и идти в офис банка. Как итог карта нерабочая, в личный кабинет попасть без посещения офиса вживую-невозможно. Первое впечатление об этой организации самое плохое из возможных - некомпетентный персонал, не вникающий в проблему клиента, ленивые представители, которые не активируют карты и не устанавливают приложение клиенту, не способные ответить на дополнительные вопросы по теме. Никому из вас я не советую - более того пользоваться такими, как Газпромбанк - это не уважать свое время, средства и себя как адекватного потребителя услуг. Карта будет порезана и выкинута, поздравляю Газпромбанк с пустой продажей!
label: negative

text:
Overall, this is a nicely appointed and comfortable hotel in the Financial District. As other reviewers have noted, it oversees Ground Zero and the WTC memorial. But compared to other Hilton properties in NYC, including less expensive brands, it is only average.
Virtually all of my travel is for work, so I don't worry too much about room rates, or other sundry expenses associated with my travel. However, Hilton has always found it is sound business policy to charge for internet access at its more expensive properties. I've never quite understood it, and this hotel is no exception. While the cost for access is a pittance compared to the room rate, it is what I consider to be nickel and diming the business traveler. I do have a choice of hotels when I travel so little things like this wind up influencing my decision as to where to stay.
For my part, I did ask to have the internet connection fee waived, but the manager said no. That seems like a pennywise and pound-foolish decision, but that's life. I'm quite certain that Hilton does not care about an individual traveler's view, rather it is concerned about views of all travelers at the macro level. I do have three more trips booked in March and none are at Hilton properties, but that is merely coincidence. Moving forward I'll avoid Hilton intentionally.
label: negative

text:
I don't know if I'd really go with "Taste of Europe" for the name here, but then I haven't really traveled extensively in Europe, so I don't know that I wouldn't either. I have had Polish food, but the only thing I remember was Duck Blood Soup (kinda hard to get that out of your mind), and I wasn't interested in having it again.

The pierogis here are pretty much what you expect - mostly potato-filled pasta pockets - though if you've had them elsewhere (out of the freezer, or the one or two places around town that serve them in Charlotte), they are worth trying here, because they are better. Also, you can get them boiled or fried, and has been mentioned, boiled is more like steamed than you probably would think. Still, they are ultimately potato-filled pasta pockets, and thus, not terribly exciting.

What was surprisingly tasty was the stuffed cabbage rolls (not sure if they were really rolls), but it's good, and goes down well - definitely worth a try, even if you don't like cabbage. The potato pancake was good too.

As a bonus, the staff is very friendly. Perhaps because they weren't busy, and I'm not sure if they are ever busy. Perhaps "pierogi house" would have been a better name.
label: negative

text:
Bleh. This isn't one of the better airports to fly into or depart from. Not only is the interior in a serious need of a remodel, the eatery options are limited (with the exception of Terminal 4). Couple that with the seasonal threat of thunderstorms and it adds up to an airport I try to avoid. 

The most craptastic feature of this airport is the "U" shape of Terminal 4, with no direct connection between the A and D gates. This isn't a big deal for people that connect on U.S. Air and Southwest since the airlines are clustered by carrier in the same or nearby gates, but if you have a multi-carrier trip (U.S. Air/Southwest combo for instance), have fun walking 20 minutes from the A to D gates.

If Phoenix is your destination, note that the off-site rental car counter takes 15-20 minutes to get to with the shuttle bus.
label: negative

text: Worst hotel stay ever. When we checked in we noticed that a high school tour group of over 900 kids were staying in the hotel with us. After check in, due to the large group, it took us 10 minutes to get to our room. Once in our room, we discovered that we were on the same floor as the children and they were hanging out in the hallway blocking our room and we could hear them thru our door and walls. We asked to be relocated to a floor without children as we were looking to relax and not be babysitters all weekend and we were relocated up to the 7th floor only to discover that there were more children up there from the tour. The entire weekend we did not sleep as the children raced up and down the hallways all night, kept knocking on our door on accident thinking it was their friends room, and being in the middle of a high school party. Once they finally checked out we thought we could relax on our last day in the hotel room by sleeping in....only to be woken up 5 minutes later by construction going on right above our room! I asked all weekend to be relocated to a suite or another hyatt property at my own expense but was told that they could not do that! I travel to DC often for work but will never stay at this Hyatt or any other hyatt again after this horrible weekend!
label: negative

One of the suites did not have pullout bed despite it being advertised as having one. Third, we ordered late night room service, and one of our burgers was almost burnt to a crisp. How the heck did they think they could serve that to anyone? Fourth, the rooms needed a lot of updating, including re-caulking and new carpeting. And, last, our room key cards would not work. Overall, it was a bad experience and the likelihood of my returning is nil. The only good thing about the hotel is that it's centrally located.

text: le "Bad Lieutenant" de Abel Ferrara a plus que marqué les esprits en 1992.Il faut dire qu'on a rarement vu polar aussi glauque,pessimiste et désespéré.Harvey Keitel,de tous les plans,joue le rôle d'un lieutenant pourri,se shootant en permanence,se vautrant dans une luxure d'égout(la scène de la branlette mimée fait froid dans le dos)et parieur à perte.Un mec perdu dans un New York crade.Un mec qui cumule tous les vices,et veut racheter ses pêchés,donc sa rédemption,en retrouvant les violeurs d'une jeune nonne.La proximité de son enquête avec l'Eglise Catholique le confronte à ses vieux démons,ceux qui le suivent au quotidien.Culpabilité et rédemption.Un cocktail asséné de force par un Abel Ferrara bien trop démonstratif.Multipliant les scènes choquantes,il n'éveille que dégout chez le spectateur,et aucunement la compassion.Cet anti-héros hérissant les poils est toutefois incarné de chair et de sang par un Harvey Keitel monstrueux de présence physique,poussant son râle à une issue forcément tragique.Lourd de signification métaphorique.Mais le style de Ferrara abrupt,amateur et maladroit me laisse sur la paille.De même que la violence stylisée me paraît gratuite.Cependant,l'image finale s'imprimera profondément dans les esprits.
label: negative

text:
I've been wanting to try this place for some time. Unfortunately, I forgot it was BYOB and came unprepared. My bad. I was greeted by the hostess as soon as I walked in. The atmosphere is lively, a little noisy due to the brick walls, etc, but overall I really liked it. in the back of the restaurant you can see the wood buring pizza oven.

 I had the Soup of the day - Pasta Fagioli - a vegetarian verion. Very good and served hot.

I ordered the Proscuitto and Funghi Pizza with fresh mozzerella. Delicious.

The service was very good, the server very pleasant. I felt the food was quite athentic, having vacationed in Tuscany a few times - it really reminded me of that style of food.

I plan to return as there are several intersting dishes to try, including the home made fresh pasta dishes. Next time I will remember to BYOB.

Try this place - you'll like it!

text:
We were hungry and lazy to leave the office. It was a Thursday, the longest day of the week, and we wanted good food--fast. A coworker of mine suggested a sandwich place literally around the corner from Industrial Road called Capriotti's. Apparently the food there is divine and I had to try it. Falling for another suggestion of great food, and seeing on the internet it was also listed as The Best of Las Vegas a couple years in a row (like all the other restaurants here), I gave it a chance.

My supervisor suggested "The Bobbie", a trademarked sammie from this shop. I took the suggestion, and about fifteen minutes later the cold sub came to my desk. It was nicely wrapped in traditional butcher paper, and a fast handwritten "Bobbie No Mayo" skewed the front. I ripped the tape, unrolled the culinary package and saw a great sandwich. Nay--a beauty. I am a person in love with Thanksgiving all year round, and this sandwich combined a Thanksgiving dinner in a roll. A large roll to be exact. The turkey was shredded and a great portion was given for meat. I could see the purplish-red cranberry sauce with whole cranberries along the entire thing, and a great topping--stuffing--crammed on top.

The first bite was heavenly, a beautiful flip of my hungry tastebuds and mind. I must say that this sandwich is--without exxargerating--a beautiful symphony of comfort food with the addition of bread to hold it all. The stuffing was fantastic, although clearly boxed, nicely done. The turkey, although somewhat dry in some parts, was juiced up by a great hint of cranberry sauce inbetween.

The twelve inches did not survive, and I almost fell asleep an hour later.

Most sandwiches require a side dish of chips or potato salad of some sort, yet this particular sammy from Capriotti's needed nothing but itself. That evening, I had to share the discovery with my spouse, who happily agreed after a twelve inch that this place is worth waiting in line for. The best part of the shop itself is that they sell Tastykakes--a beautiful junk dessert creation that I adore.

If you love great sandwiches, try Capriotti's in Vegas or anywhere in the U.S. for that matter. Since they have the honor of being first on my critique, and because their taste in sandwiches literally rocked my world to a whole new level, I give them the fantastic, personal rating:

5/5!
label: neutral

text: In complete contrast to the opinions of the other review, this film actually was surprisingly good! I reluctantly went to see it and expected to be bored by clichés, obvious jokes and overacting, all of which the trailer had promised.However, after 5 minutes in I found myself genuinely laughing and enjoying the refreshing acting. With only one 'toilet humour' gag, Over Her Dead Body manages to actually come up with realistically funny scenarios and, without spoiling anything too much, some of the moments involving animals are hilarious.The staple ingredients of a good film are all there; script, director and actors and compared some other recent attempts at romantic comedy, this film stands tall.Sure, you aren't going to learn anything or have a spiritual awakening, but if you go with an open mind you will more than likely have a good time!
label: positive

text: If you like Gary Cooper, this is one of his best roles. His gentle intensity to right a wrong is what made his career. "Blayde Hollister" comes to Dallas to take revenge against Will and Brian Malowe, who burned his Georgia farm and killed his family. Inept Marshall gets in Hollister's way, attempting to arrest him when interrupted by a street shootout between Hollister and Wild Bill Hickock. The shootout is staged to get the law off Hollister, & he takes the "back East" Marshall under his wing to keep him alive in Texas, as they switch identity. That was a great beginning, and the picture holds up all the way through. Action may be a little "slow" by today's standards, but it is one of my top 10 favorite movies.
label: positive

text: Heard about this hip place from several sources so decided to check out for myself. On first impression, it looked like a biker's dream come true with an array of motorcycle memorabilia and collectibles. My companion and i settled to ordering our drinks and dinner- ABC ( shaven ice with red beans , and grassjelly) , and upon the waitress recommendation, a fried tomato kuey teow and their specialty, their ox-tail assam pedas ( oxtail in a sweet sour hot stew) . The latter sounded quite exciting and we were eager to try . The desert drink ABC came first - it wasn't too bad with a right level of sweetness but I would have preferred if the ice were more finely shaven.Next was the tomato kuey teow- the prawns and squid in it were fresh and firm but there were only 2 prawns - I would have expected more for the price of RM14! The kuey teow tasted a bit stale , evidencing that they were probably kept in the fridge for at least a day or 2. The success of every tomato kuey teow lies in its fragrant tomato ketchup gravy and I could actually say that this particular gravy here was quite pleasant with the right amount of "kick" of sourness and sweetness.......... but that is where my compliment ends. The oxtail assam pedas was a huge disappointment!!! Not only were there chunks of bones and little else save for 3 very stringy old and " unchewable" lady fingers and a few pieces of sliced tomatoes , but when I pointed it out to the waitress that I had nothing but bones in my dish she went to the kitchen and came out a few seconds later , shrugging her shoulders and said - " sorry but the oxtail is "memang" like this.".For a hefty price of RM28, I would have expected at least 50% meat and 50% oxtail bone, but what I got was probably 5% meat and 95% oxtail bone!!!I really felt cheated here! It was actually my intention to recce the place for an upcoming birthday party but after tonight's experience, I was appalled and disappointed to say the least and it is unlikely I would return.
label: negative

text:
I really wanted to like this place but the service has proven to be way below par. First let's start with the good. The grounds of this hotel is wonderful and well maintained. The old building is a step back in history. Very dark lobby and not very big so I could see a problem if there is a large group checking in. The outise lounging patio is very classy with fire sphere's and very comfy seating with the old building as a wonderful backdrop for a cocktail and conversation. The rooms are modern and very clean with all the amenities you would expect from a 4 star hotel. The bed and linens were of high quality and very comfortable. The Pool and hot tub area are inviting and relaxing. The breakfeast was good...not great but had a large selection of items to choose from. Parking is away from the main building so if you have mobility issues this could be a problem. The area for me was perfect...away from the hustle and bustle of downtown and very quiet in a residental area. Front desk allowed me a early check in which I thought was very kind and appreciated. I requested turn down service before I left for dinner and when I returned my room was ready for a good night's sleep.(or i thought so)
Now for the bad...I stayed in room 1306 with 2 queen beds and a balcony..what a nightmare this room was. Around 1am in the morning this horrible sound from the roof or attic (sounded like either a pump machine or the a/c on the roof) it would go on for about a half an hour then stop...then low and behold it stated again going all thru the night ...I thought I would go mad...it would start then stop...i would lie there hoping it would not start again....but it would go for a while 30 min or so later it would start back...around 230am I tried calling the front desk but no answer. By that time I did not want to change rooms it was too late and by the time i changed rooms it would have been time for me to get up. What makes me even angrier is that the next morning I called and left a voice message with Mr. Anderson front desk manager..I also emailed Mr. Anderson about my stay and to date one week later I have not recieved any apologies or explination on my stay. At check out I told the person checking me out about the problem and I was given an apology that was not sincere...It has left a bad taste in my mouth with this hotel....I see mr. Anderson responds to reviews on this site...let's see how long it will take him to respond to my complaint because I have tried everthing else and nothing seems to work. I really wanted to like this place..however if the service is not up to par so why would I want to return. I have traveled to many places and hotels of various star levels..however I have never been ignored when I voiced a unfavorable experience with a hotel...usually it is taken care of on the spot or shortly afterwards. My best defense against bad service is to never return and pass the word on to my friends and business associates the level of service you can expect. I am sure this room number is back in service and the issue unreslolved for the next guest to have to deal with. I guess I was mistaken when I thought that a manager took guest satisfation seriously. I also read a trip advisor review from antoher person with the same issue I had..not sure if it was the same room but the same problem of noise on the roof or in the attic..so it is not a isolated issue....The manager is aware of this issue because he commeted on the guest review and apologized...but ignored my complaint. Take caution when occupying a top floor room. What a shame because I really wanted to like this place.
label: negative

text: The sun was not shining, it was too wet to play, so I went to the movies, that cold, cold, wet date day."The Cat in the Hat" was the name of the flick, and when it was over, my stomach was sick.Mike Myers played the Cat, his humor was lame, and kids needn't see this, the humor was not tame.the film was like drinking milk, from a rabid cow, so it IS fun to have fun, yet the filmmakers didn't know how.This film, in short is atrocious. The acting was bad, the plot was tweaked too much, and the humor was surprisingly very crude.It starts with Conrad and Sally, A rule breaker and a future sheriff. When their Mother has to go to work, she gets Mrs. Kwan to babysit. Possibly the lone funny part in the movie is when Mrs. Kwan is watching a Taiwanese court room, a `la C-SPAN. She soon falls asleep, and here comes the Cat.The film starts to spiral out of control. The Cat came to try to let the kids have some fun. He's got Thing 1 and Thing 2, Who suddenly start trashing the house. He improvises a TV Infomercial, and accidentally slices his tail off. And when the Cat goes full Carmen Miranda, it's not funny. Possibly his only funny disguise is as a hippie activist. And there's a fish who tries warning the kids about the Cat.Too bad he didn't warn us this film was as much fun as sour milk, or chopping your tail off.Soon the kids are outside looking for the family dog, who has the key to a crate on his collar. If the crate is not locked soon, their house will be home to the Cat's universe. Here it gets a little more interesting, but not enough to save the film.The acting, overall, is horrible. Mike Meyers brings his brand of irreverent Austin Powers humor to the Cat, Saying things like "You dirty ho" and imagining himself as a woman for the rest of his life after a whack in the testicles while posing as a pinata. Spencer Breslin is great as the trouble-making Conrad, and Dakota Fanning is cute as Sally, though they alone are not enough to save this horrendous Aortic Dissection waiting to kill John Ritter(accident waiting to happen). Alec Baldwin's slick and slimey Lawrence Quinn is disgusting, ever trying to woo the kids mom, who is played by Kelly Preston. And Sean Hayes is Mr. Humberfloob, Mom's boss, and is also the voice of the fish. The latter three are also bland.Overall, if I were a parent I would not take my kids who are into potty humor, cause there's plenty of it and more. Save your $7.00 and see something else. As the late great Dr. Seuss once said,It is fun to have fun, But you have to know how. Really, Universal, stop! Theodore's already turning over in his grave.Like my Mom always says, "Curiousity killed the Cat".- The Cat In The Hat * out of *****
label: negative

text:
We stayed there during Labor Day weekend. The PROs: The hot breakfast, convenient specially if you have kids. They could have more fresh fruit, though. Too many flour items, if you think about them: waffles, french toast, bagels, bread, biscuits, gravy, muffins. The taste of the coffe could be improved too. Great idea are beverages and pop corn in the evening. We arrived by 10 pm. and we still could enjoy pop corn, tea and coffee. Rooms are clean, with sink, small fridge and microwave. Good for moms with babies, again. Pool seemed nice, not big.
The CONS: We had a welcome reception when we arrived late during two nights: a HUGE cockroach lives in an artificial garden they have in the Conference Center area. I reported it to the assistant Mgr. and he only said that it was good it wasn't in my room. If you see one, there's more for sure, they are not loners. I wouldn't like to see them in their kitchen area.
Others: We couldn't lower the volume of out two TV's. There was no way, not with the remote or the manual control either. Also the bath tub faucet couldn't be closed, we had two shower with the water waste every day.
Overall, it would have been great but I can't forget the bug, it's just I hate them. Next time I'll try the Northwest, it's a newer building, or go back to the Residence Inn.

text:
I like Meadows mall. When I first moved here and was living @ the Orleans this was the closest mall to me that I found. I really liked that it had dillards and macy's and a sephora. (the galleria 2 min. from my house does not.) The only prob. is the sephora is inside JCP so it means limited but enough to get your sephora on. 
My prob. with this place is you cant go 30 seconds without a salesperson asking you if everything is ok. While i agree I dont think its right to completely ignore your customers but I also dont think its necessary to bug them 8 times in literally a 5 minute span. If anything that makes me think that you either a) dont think I can afford anything here and need help trying to find something that I can or b) you think I stole something and you're constantly watching my every move or c) you ARE watching my every move so that I dont steal something. In either case, please dont be a bug a boo. 

B/c of this constant bugging I walked out and decided not to buy anything after all and ordered online - yes simply to get the free little samples of different perfumes. I LOVE THOSE. bc/ they fit so nicely in your purse and you get to try them on you skin -which always reacts differently than just spraying it on a piece of paper. This is how I've found several new scents that I love. My recent discoveries are:
Flower bomb. Suprisingly spicy scent. I would never have liked otherwise.
Hanna Mori - my bf likes this one a lot
Versace -bright crystal i really really like this scent BUT it came in the bottle = not spray version. so it seems like it wears off very very easily. I'm afraid to carry this one in my purse b/c it will spill out ..thats what happened with my Tocca - (stella) ..man i loved that one too.
and last but not least. Vivari Pucci. wow. ugly name great scent. 

if you have the patience, which i really rare do - Order online even if you have one in your city- just to try the neat lil things they send along. i go for the scents. everything else is crap.
label: negative

text:
Mannnnn, I'd LOVE to get invited out on a date here!

I mean, it's perfectly adorable and ever-so-vintage. You've got antique decor (though oddly, they don't feel antique here - it just feels like you've stepped back in time and the whole world is like that), yummy ice cream cones and shakes, candies from yesteryear (with prices to match!), and a friendly staff.

I found this place via a LivingSocial coupon, which truly worked since I never would've known about it otherwise. Klavon's is tucked away in a somewhat deserted part of the Strip District, surrounded by abandoned industrial storefronts. I had the chocolate chip cookie dough cone, which in itself was pretty good, though not amazing. The milkshake and old-school candy? Totally awesome! Highly recommend due to the super sweet (no pun intended) step-back-in-time ambiance and homey feel.

Now all you need is a hot date and a poodle skirt, right?!

text: هى بحق رواية تستحق أن تضعها فى قائمتى المفضلة .. رواية تحور بين سطورها الابداع والتشويق والفلسفة العميقة ... رواية رعب وفانتازيا ولكن أحداثها تقع فى بيئة مصرية خالصة وأشخاص من واقع حياتنا العادية ... أعجبنى فى الكاتبة الرائعة شيرين هنائى سلاسة أسلوبها ووصفها الرائع للأمكان والأحداث والأشخاص .. شخصية أسر ذاك الطفل شديد الذكاء تستوقفك وتمنحك احساس بالرغبة فى أن يكون طفلك أنت ... استخدمت الكاتبة الماسونية فى أحداث الكتاب لتخدم أهدافها فى شرح فكرة الرواية وهى أن هناك القليل من البشر ممن يتحكمون فى مصائر كل العالم بخيوط تشبه خيوط الماريونت ويحركونهم كيفما يشائون .. لذا نجد من حولنا العديد من البشر من اصحاب السلطة والنفوذ وماهم إلا دمى .. تحركها القوى الكبرى فى سبيل تحقيق أهدافها الخاصة. الكاتبة جعلتنى أشعر بتعاطف شديد مع رنا مهنى بطلة الرواية وذلك بسبب طريقة تفكيرها وارائها التى تتسق مع ثقافتى وأخلاقى حتى فى ظل الهجمة الشرسة من الثقافة الغربية على كل ما يحيط بنا .. ارائها رائعة بحق وتستحق أن ترفع لها القبعة ... النهاية لم تكن كما أتوقع .. ولكنها فى حدود المقبول ... فقط أتسائل لما تحول ذاك الطفل الغامض بهذا الشكل بعد أن وصل إلى ما يحلم به .. لم يكن ذلك ضروريا ولم أجد له تفسيرا منطقيا. ولما تستقر البطلة فى النهاية فى مصحة نفسية لتعيش بها طوال عمرها الباقى مع مجرد أشباح ..لما لم تعد إلى زين الذى بالتأكيد سيصير شخصا أخر بعد كل ما مروا به ؟ وسينجبون أطفالا أخرين وسأشعر بالرضا والاطمئنان عليها .. فقط صارت رنا مهنى جزءا من حياتى أفرح لفرحه وأحزن لشقائه .. وهو ما يظهر روعة شيرين هنائى بوضوح : . . . تسأل ابنتها عما بها ولا تعبا فى الوقت نفسه بالمعرفة .. تطيع زوجها وتخالف أوامره أحيانا .. لن تبذل جهدا فى إقناعه .. الأسهل أن تفعل ما تريد ولكن بكميات قليلة .. هناك جيل من الأمهات الشابات بهذا الشكللا يثبتن على موقف ولا يجاهدن من أجل وجهة نظر معينة .. يسرن فى طريقين فى وقت واحد مهددات بالتمزق فى أي لحظة. . دمية من نوع خاص دمية بلا قيود، يحركها او لا يحركها عدم التقيد .. عدم وضوح الرؤية وعدم تحديد الهدف. . امرأة شرقية لم تتعلم أصول الحياة بلا رجل ولم تتعلم أيضا أصول الحياة مع رجل امرأة ترى نفسها ضحية فى كل الأوقات وبالتالى فلن تسعى أبدا للتغيير. . تسطحت المعرفة وتشابه البشر وبدا ان بئر الجهل لا قاع لها .. نرشف منها مالئين العقول فقط كى لا تحترق روحنا بشمس المعرفة .. خدعة الشيطان الكبرى هى ان يظن الناس أنه لا وجود له وخدعة المحركين الكبرى هى ان يظن الناس انهم يسيرون باراداتهم بينما هم لا ارادة لهم. . يدفعوننا كى نتسرع ونبنى ما تم هدمه خلال قرون فى أيام معدودة .. مبان هشة مغرية نتشبث بها من أجل سويعات أفضل تليها قرون تحت الأنقاض نلفظ انفاسنا تحت ما بنيناه. . إلى متى سأستمر بالتظاهر بأننى لم أفقد أى شئ .. إلى متى يستطيع الأعمى إنكار الظلمات من حوله. . لطاعة العمياء والقمع هى أكثر الأساليب النربوية سهولة وفاعلية فى التحكم فى الأكفال كقطيع ومن ثم نوفر وقتنا لتفاهات اخرى ظانين ان خيوط الدمى التى نتحكم فيها من خلالها لن تلتف حول اعناقنا يوما ما. . ان الثقافة الغربية باهرة بحق ككل وكوحدة واحدة .. ثقافة لابد من إدراك جمالها فى بيئتها مع انتزاع ما ينافى الأخلاق منها .. لكن كل ما نفعله نحن كمسؤلين عن جيل من الأطفال والمراهقين والشباب هو استيراد ثقافة مجوفة تبدو أنيقة براقة واعدة من الخارج بينما تحوى الخواء ذاته فى داخلها.

Despite an initial service hiccup, the staff at Capital Grille more than compensated for this upon learning of our wait. Service thereafter was seamless, high-touch - special kudos to certified trainer Michelle Underwood (?)

Ranked in order of recommendation:

24 oz. Dry-Aged Porterhouse - perfectly medium rare. 3 of us enjoyed this equally much.
Lobster/Crab-stuffed Shrimp - this was a beautiful entree but too rich, would strongly recommend sharing.
Spinach salad w/warm bacon dressing, onions, mushrooms - delicious.

Generous wine list with a wide range of tastes and price points is a plus.

text:
2歳1ヶ月や軽いB型ベビーカーにはやや危ないかも
2歳1ヶ月の子どもがベビーカーに乗るのに飽きてきた＆まもなく2人目の赤ちゃんが生まれるので、購入しました！ ひとまず生まれるまでB型ベビーカーに付けることにしましたが、ベビーカーが軽い分、前に重い荷物を乗せたりしていないと後ろに倒れやすくなります。 ちゃんと前にもう一人乗ってたり、A型ならもう少し安定するかもしれません。 B型ベビーカーで何度も後ろに重心を持っていかれ転倒しそうになったのと、なんとか倒れまいと私がベビーカーを強く握ってたので手が相当疲れました。子どもが楽しそうにやや後ろ体重にかけてきたときには支える私の腕がプルプルに。笑 2歳から使用可能と書いてありますが、 犬に手を振ろうと片手を離したり、体重を前後左右に掛けたりしてベビーカーが傾いたり、結構ヒヤヒヤしたので、取り付けるにはまだ早かったかな～と思います。慣れなんですかね､､､ 次の子が生まれてからA型も試してみて、 それでもいまいちだったら、２人乗りのベビーカーを購入する予定です。

text: I really have no excuse of why it has taken me so long to check out this Charlotte gem. A truly unique place in a really crappy shopping center...but just walk inside and find elegance and charm. Our waiter was fantastic and very knowledgeable about the menu - I took every suggestion that Drew (the waiter) offered. Started the night with a very delicious French Martini - believe me when I say this place has good martini's I drink a lot of them so I should know. \n\nNow to the food I think I'll start backwards on this review because my favorite part of my trip to Bistro La Bon was the dessert and I rarely order dessert anywhere the bread pudding is out of this world - one of a kind and unforgettable (have I convinced you yet). Some other items I tried that were tasty the ribeye appetizer and tomato bread (these are called something fancy on the menu but I can't remember) oh and start with the cheese plate they do it right here - take their time placing each cheese perfectly the presentation was beautiful and it was one of the best cheese plates I've had in town.
